"""
mkt-context: Job chapters 12–14
Job's sarcastic reply to Zophar and wisdom-hymn (ch12), his judicial challenge
to the friends and direct address to God (ch13), meditation on human mortality
and longing for post-mortem vindication (ch14).
75 verses: ch12 (25), ch13 (28), ch14 (22).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOB_CONTEXT_12_14 = {
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Job's reply to Zophar opens the third and final speech of the first disputation round (Job 12-14 answer Zophar's speech in ch11). In ANE literary context, the disputation text was a well-established genre — Babylonian and Sumerian examples survive (the Babylonian Theodicy, the Dialogue of a Master and His Slave) in which two speakers debate the justice of suffering. Job's speech is the most developed example in the Hebrew Bible, and the sarcastic tone of v.2 signals that the genre conventions are now being transgressed: instead of a balanced debate, Job is about to demolish the friends' claims to wisdom authority.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The biting sarcasm 'No doubt you are the people, and wisdom will die with you' targets the social position the three friends occupy. In the ancient Near East, wisdom was not personal intellectual property but communal and traditionally transmitted — the <em>ḥăkāmîm</em> (sages) were professionals who had trained in scribal schools and claimed authority from inherited tradition. Eliphaz's appeal to communal investigation in 5:27 ('this we have searched out; it is true') is exactly this claim. Job's irony attacks the pretension that the friends are the exclusive custodians of a wisdom tradition that Job lacks; he is contesting the authority structure itself, not merely their individual arguments.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The phrase 'I am not inferior to you' is a formal claim to equal intellectual standing in the wisdom disputation. In ancient wisdom circles, one's standing to dispute depended on demonstrating equivalent qualifications — the sage who could not establish such standing was dismissed without a hearing. Job's claim is socially transgressive in the honor-shame world: a suffering man claiming equality with three established wisdom figures who have gathered to counsel him. The rhetorical question 'who does not know such things as these?' is a further move: Job concedes that the friends' theology is commonplace, which is itself the critique — their wisdom is too easy, too formulaic, not responsive to his specific case.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Being 'a laughingstock to his friends' describes Job's social position in a culture organized by honor and shame. In the honor-shame world of the ancient Near East, public mockery by one's social equals represented catastrophic status loss. Job's complaint is not merely emotional but social: the disputation has placed him in the position of an inferior whose claims are treated as objects of ridicule. The phrase 'one who called to God and he answered him' refers to Job's former status as a man whose prayers were effective — a mark of divine favor. The friends' theology would have to concede this was once real, which makes his current suffering even more theologically inexplicable on their terms.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'In the thought of one who is at ease there is contempt for misfortune.' The social observation about how prosperity breeds contempt for the suffering is grounded in the ANE patron-client system. In the ancient world, the wealthy and powerful could afford philosophical equanimity about suffering precisely because they were not experiencing it. The friends' comfortable positions make their retribution theology cost-free for them: they can prescribe patient submission to suffering because they are not submitting. This verse anticipates what liberation theology would later identify as the epistemological advantage of the sufferer — those not affected by a problem cannot be fully trusted to diagnose it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The tents of robbers are at peace, and those who provoke God are secure' — Job raises the most direct challenge to retribution theology from within the wisdom tradition itself. The 'prosperity of the wicked' was a recognized problem in ANE wisdom literature: Babylonian wisdom texts (the Dialogue of Pessimism, the Babylonian Theodicy) and Egyptian wisdom texts (the Dispute of a Man Who Contemplates Suicide with His Soul) all acknowledge that the morally simple equation righteousness = prosperity breaks down in lived experience. Job's point is that the observation-based theology the friends claim is simply false empirically. The phrase 'into whose hand God brought him' is the most radical assertion: divine causation of unjust prosperity is directly attributed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'But ask the beasts, and they will teach you' — the call to learn from the created order deploys a recognized ANE wisdom epistemology. In Egyptian wisdom tradition (Amenemope, Ptah-hotep), the observation of nature was a standard source of wisdom instruction. The animals, birds, earth, and fish are proposed as instructors because they operate according to divinely-established patterns without the ability to construct self-serving ideological frameworks. The irony is deliberate: the non-rational creation has access to truth about divine sovereignty that the three rational sages have missed by over-systematizing their theology into a mechanical formula.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The inclusion of the earth itself as a teacher ('speak to the earth, and it will teach you') reflects the ancient Israelite understanding that creation encodes divine wisdom — a theme developed in Proverbs 8 (Wisdom present at creation), Psalm 19 (the heavens declaring glory), and the whirlwind speeches of Job 38-41. The verb 'speak to the earth' may also reflect background in nature omens: in Mesopotamian divination, the behavior of animals, plants, and natural phenomena was systematically interpreted as divine communication. Job democratizes this: all creation testifies, not just trained diviners with specialized esoteric knowledge.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Who among all these does not know that the hand of YHWH has done this?' — the shift from the generic divine names (<em>ʾĒl</em>, <em>ʾělōhîm</em>) throughout Job's poetic dialogues to <em>YHWH</em> (the covenant name) is rare and significant. Some manuscripts read the generic name here, but if <em>YHWH</em> is original, it signals that the creation-testimony argument points specifically to the covenant God rather than a generic divine power. The creation-testimony argument functions simultaneously as a polemic against the friends' mechanical theology and as the basis for Job's next claim in v.10: divine ownership of all life is the foundation of divine sovereignty over all circumstances.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'In his hand is the life of every living thing and the breath of all mankind.' The phrase <em>nep̄eš kol-ḥay</em> (soul/life of every living thing) reflects the ancient understanding that life itself is a divine loan — breathed in at creation (Gen 2:7: <em>nišmaṯ ḥayyîm</em>) and recalled at death. In ANE thought, this divine ownership of life was expressed through the practice of dedicating firstfruits to the deity: the divine ownership of all life was the theological foundation for the firstfruits system. The implication for Job's argument: divine sovereignty over life is total and direct, making the friends' mechanistic retribution system an inadequate account of how God actually governs creation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Does not the ear test words as the palate tastes food?' — the comparison of intellectual discernment to gustatory taste was a conventional wisdom analogy in the ancient Near East. Egyptian wisdom texts frequently compare wisdom to food and its acquisition to eating and digesting. The ear as the primary organ of wisdom reception reflects an oral transmission culture: wisdom was learned by hearing from elders and teachers, not primarily by reading. The analogy serves Job's argument: just as the palate distinguishes wholesome from corrupt food, the ear can distinguish true wisdom from the friends' platitudes — and Job's ear has made that judgment against the friends' speeches.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Wisdom is with the aged, and understanding in length of days' — Job appears to concede the friends' appeal to tradition and seniority. But the verse functions as a setup for the divine-wisdom hymn of vv.13-25: with God there is a wisdom that transcends and overturns all the wisdom of the aged and powerful. The appeal to the aged in wisdom literature was standard: Prov 16:31, Sir 25:4-6, and the Egyptian instruction literature all present the elder's authority as grounded in accumulated experience. Job uses the conventional form to make an unconventional point: the tradition itself testifies to a divine sovereignty that the friends' theology has failed to account for.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'With God are wisdom and might; he has counsel and understanding.' The divine attribute list draws on royal ideology: wisdom (<em>ḥokmāh</em>), might (<em>gəḇûrāh</em>), counsel (<em>ʿēṣāh</em>), and understanding (<em>təḇûnāh</em>) were the four attributes of the ideal ANE king who governed justly and victoriously. In Isaiah 11:2, these same four attributes are ascribed to the coming Davidic king anointed by YHWH's spirit. Job's hymn claims divine wisdom is comprehensive and sovereign — far beyond what the friends have captured in their retribution formula — and proceeds to demonstrate this through a catalogue of divine sovereignty over every power structure.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'If he tears down, none can rebuild; if he shuts a man in, none can open.' The rhetoric of divine exclusivity uses architectural imagery: what God demolishes cannot be rebuilt by any other power. In ANE culture, the ability to build and destroy cities was the supreme demonstration of royal power — Babylonian chronicles record the building and destruction of cities as proof of divine favor or disfavor with kings. Job's argument reverses the friends' theology: if God is truly sovereign over all building and destroying, then human theological systems cannot reliably predict what God will build or destroy, including Job's own situation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'If he withholds the waters, they dry up; if he sends them out, they overwhelm the land.' Sovereign control of water was the most critical political and religious issue in the ancient Near East. In Mesopotamia, the entire economy depended on the Tigris-Euphrates system; in Canaan, the contest between Baal (storm/rain deity) and YHWH was fundamentally about who controlled the rains. The reference to withholding and releasing waters echoes the flood narrative and the drought/rain cycle controlled by YHWH in the Elijah narrative (1 Kgs 17-18). Job's point: the same divine power that controls weather controls his suffering — and is not constrained by any human formula.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'With him are strength and sound wisdom; the deceived and the deceiver are his.' The pairing of the deceived and deceiver as both belonging to God is a sophisticated theological claim: divine sovereignty extends even to the structures of deception in human society. In ANE thinking, cosmic chaos and moral disorder were often attributed to demonic forces opposing divine order (Tiamat, Mot, various evil spirits in Mesopotamian texts). Job's radical monotheism insists that even the deceiving and the deceived are under divine control — a claim that anticipates the prologue's portrait of the Adversary operating only within YHWH's explicit permission structure.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'He leads counselors away stripped and makes fools of judges.' In the ancient Near East, royal counselors (<em>yōʿăṣîm</em>) and judges were the highest civic offices, their authority grounded in specialized knowledge and divine appointment. To be led away 'stripped' (barefoot — the sign of defeat and captivity) was the ultimate honor-shame reversal: the victory parade displaying captives barefoot and in chains was the standard form of royal triumph iconography in Egyptian and Assyrian art. Job's hymn uses these images to show that divine sovereignty overturns every human power structure, including the wisdom authorities the three friends claim to represent.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'He loosens the bonds of kings and binds a waistcloth on their loins.' Kings in the ancient Near East wore distinctive garments (royal robes, the royal belt/sash) as symbols of office. The loosening of their bonds and replacement with a servant's waistcloth (<em>ʾēzôr</em>) is the total status reversal. The victory reliefs of Ramesses II and Sennacherib depicted captive kings stripped of their royal insignia as proof of divine punishment. Job's hymn activates this political iconography to assert divine sovereignty over even the greatest earthly powers — and implicitly, over Eliphaz, Bildad, and Zophar's claims to authority.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'He leads priests away stripped and overthrows the mighty.' Priests (<em>kōhănîm</em>) are included alongside counselors, judges, and kings in the catalogue of the powerful whom God overturns. In the ancient world, priestly authority was the institutional form of divine access — priests mediated between the human and divine realms. Their stripping and overthrow signals that no institutional claim to divine access is secure against actual divine sovereignty. The irony directed at the three friends: they claim priestly/wise authority to interpret God's ways, but the very tradition they invoke testifies to divine freedom to overturn all such institutional claims.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'He deprives of speech those who are trusted and takes away the discernment of the elders.' The loss of eloquence was a profound social catastrophe in an oral culture. In the ancient world, wisdom was demonstrated through speech: the sage who could not speak was no longer a sage. The elders (<em>zəqēnîm</em>) who lose their <em>ṭāʿam</em> (taste/discernment — the same word used in the palate metaphor of v.11) are the same class the friends represent. This verse prepares for Job's direct confrontation in ch13: if God removes the speech and discernment of those who claim authority, the friends' confident speeches are themselves potentially evidence of something other than divine wisdom.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'He pours contempt on princes and loosens the belt of the strong.' Contempt (<em>bûz</em>) poured on princes (<em>nəḏîḇîm</em>, the noble/generous class) is the ANE social reversal par excellence. Honor was the primary social currency of the ancient world: princes lost in battle were stripped of their belts and displayed as captives. The imagery echoes Egyptian and Mesopotamian victory iconography. Psalm 107:40 quotes this verse almost verbatim — the same divine action that terrifies Job in his suffering is celebrated as salvation in the Psalm by those it delivers from oppression, demonstrating that the perspective of the observer determines the experience of the same divine act.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'He uncovers the deeps out of darkness and brings deep darkness to light.' In ancient cosmology, the deep (<em>təhôm</em>) was the primordial watery chaos that preceded creation (Gen 1:2) and still lay beneath the ordered world. Divine control over the deep was the mark of the Creator-God — Marduk's defeat of Tiamat in the Babylonian Enuma Elish is the Mesopotamian parallel to YHWH's command over the primordial waters in Genesis 1 and Psalm 104. Job's hymn claims that the same divine power that brought order out of chaos can bring hidden things to light — anticipating the whirlwind speeches' meditation on creation's mysteries in chs. 38-41.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'He makes nations great, and he destroys them; he enlarges nations, and leads them away.' The sovereign control of national destinies was a central claim of Israelite theology expressed in the Deuteronomistic historical framework and the prophetic literature. In ANE political theology, the rise and fall of nations was attributed to the favor or disfavor of national deities — the Mesha Stele describes YHWH's anger with Israel as the cause of Moab's victories. Job's universal scope ('nations' without ethnic distinction) reflects the wisdom tradition's international perspective and positions YHWH as sovereign of all history, not merely Israel's patron deity.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'He takes away understanding from the chiefs of the people of the earth and makes them wander in a trackless waste.' The image of wandering in a trackless waste (<em>tōhû</em>, the same word as Gen 1:2's formless void and Deut 32:10's wilderness without path) was a potent symbol of divine judgment in ANE culture. Desert wilderness was not merely geographically dangerous — it was the space outside the ordered world of civilization and cult. To be sent into the <em>tōhû</em> was expulsion from the realm of divine blessing into the realm of chaos. The chiefs of the earth, by divine action, lose their navigational capacity and become wanderers in the space their wisdom was supposed to prevent.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'They grope in the dark without light, and he makes them stagger like a drunkard.' The darkness-as-disorientation image resonates with the Deuteronomistic covenant curse (Deut 28:28-29: divine judgment produces blindness; you shall grope at noonday as the blind grope in darkness) and with the prophetic tradition's use of darkness as a symbol of divine judgment (Amos 5:18-20: the Day of YHWH is darkness, not light). The staggering drunkard was a recognized ANE symbol of political and military disorder — defeated armies are described as staggering like drunkards in the Assyrian annals. Job's hymn ends with a comprehensive picture of divine sovereignty over every human power, positioning him to make his direct judicial challenge in ch13.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The opening of chapter 13 is explicitly retrospective: 'my eye has seen all this, my ear has heard and understood it.' Job claims the same empirical knowledge as the friends — visual and auditory experience — the standard wisdom epistemology. The paired organs of sight (<em>ʿayin</em>) and hearing (<em>ʾōzen</em>) echo Job's palate/ear analogy in 12:11. By claiming equal empirical access, Job eliminates the friends' epistemic advantage and prepares to make a higher-stakes argument: he knows all they know, and more.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'What you know, I also know; I am not inferior to you.' The disputational context of wisdom competition required formal claims to equal or superior understanding before arguing. In the ancient educational tradition, the master-student relationship was structured by acknowledged hierarchy — a student could not directly contradict a teacher without first establishing equal standing. Job's claim is socially transgressive: a suffering man claiming equality with three established wisdom figures who have gathered to counsel him. The social inversion is calculated: in the honor-shame world, Job's claim to equality despite his low status is itself a formal act of defiance that demands the dispute be adjudicated on its merits.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'But I would speak to the Almighty, and I desire to argue my case with God.' The shift from arguing with the friends to arguing with God is the formal declaration of the <em>rîb</em> (covenant lawsuit). In Israelite legal culture, the <em>rîb</em> was a specific forensic form in which one party brought accusations before a judge or the divine assembly — prophets regularly used the form to bring YHWH's accusations against Israel (Isa 1:2-3; Hos 4:1-3; Mic 6:1-8). Job inverts the form: he demands that YHWH be both the defendant and the judge. The logical paradox of demanding justice from the very judge who seems to be the adversary is the book's central legal tension, resolved only when YHWH speaks from the whirlwind in chs. 38-41.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'As for you, you whitewash with lies; you are worthless physicians, all of you.' The 'physicians of no value' (<em>rōp̄ĕʾê ʾelaḵ</em>) was a recognized social critique in the ancient world. Medical practice in the ancient Near East combined priestly and wisdom functions — the Mesopotamian <em>āšipu</em> (exorcist-healer) and the <em>asû</em> (physician) used both medical and ritual knowledge. A healer who could not heal was not just professionally incompetent but potentially dangerous, as false diagnosis could prevent proper treatment. Job's accusation uses the medical metaphor to indict the friends' counsel as actively harmful: their theological whitewashing (<em>ṭāpaḥ šāqer</em>, plastering with falsehood) prevents the accurate diagnosis his situation requires.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Oh that you would keep silent, and it would be your wisdom!' The ironic counsel that silence would have been wiser reflects the wisdom tradition's own teaching on speech discipline. Proverbs repeatedly valorizes the person who speaks little: 'Even a fool who keeps silent is considered wise; when he closes his lips, he is deemed intelligent' (Prov 17:28); 'let your words be few' (Eccl 5:2). Silence in the face of incomprehensible suffering was an honored response in the wisdom tradition — the three friends initially sat in silence for seven days (2:13), which was the appropriate mourning companion protocol. By speaking, they broke that protocol and entered the dangerous territory of theodicy.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Hear now my argument and listen to the pleadings of my lips.' Job uses the formal forensic vocabulary of the covenant lawsuit: <em>ṯôkaḥaṯ</em> (argument, reproof, legal case) and <em>rîḇôṯ</em> (pleadings, legal contestations). These are the technical terms of the ancient Near Eastern court proceeding. In the Israelite legal system, the court of elders at the city gate was the primary judicial forum — the same setting Job describes from his former prominence in 29:7. By using this legal vocabulary formally, Job frames his speech as a judicial proceeding rather than emotional complaint, demanding the friends take his argument seriously as a formal legal claim.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Will you speak falsely for God and speak deceitfully for him?' The accusation of legal false witness is the most serious charge in Israelite jurisprudence: the ninth commandment (Exod 20:16) prohibits bearing false witness. In Deut 19:16-21, a false witness received the punishment that was due to the accused. Job inverts the friends' position: they present themselves as God's defenders, but in speaking falsely about Job's guilt, they become false witnesses before the divine judge whose standards they claim to uphold. The friends cannot be both accurate theological authorities and false witnesses — if they are wrong about Job, their theology is wrong; if their theology is right, they are bearing false witness.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Will you show partiality toward him? Will you plead the case for God?' The accusation of showing partiality (<em>nāśāʾ pānîm</em>, to lift the face, to show favoritism) draws on the judicial principle that justice requires impartiality (Lev 19:15; Deut 1:17). Showing partiality toward God — the most powerful party — in a legal proceeding violates the fundamental principle of impartial judgment: justice always favors the weak against the strong (Prov 22:22-23; Isa 1:17). The friends, by assuming God must be right and Job must be wrong regardless of evidence, have violated the foundational legal principle. In the honor-shame culture, respecting the person of the powerful was a recognized form of corruption that the prophets repeatedly condemned.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Will it be well with you when he searches you out? Or can you deceive him, as one deceives a man?' The warning that divine examination will expose the friends' false witness uses the standard ANE theology of divine omniscience. In Mesopotamian religion, the sun-deity Shamash (also the god of justice) was believed to see all human actions and expose hidden things. The Psalms of innocence in Mesopotamian literature (corresponding to Israel's individual lament psalms) frequently appeal to the divine knowledge of the supplicant's true character. Job turns this theology against the friends: if God truly searches all things, God will find their false counsel, not merely Job's alleged sin.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'He will surely rebuke you if in secret you show partiality.' The divine rebuke of partial judgment draws on the Israelite understanding of the divine court as the ultimate court of appeal. Psalm 82 depicts YHWH judging the divine assembly for failing to render just verdicts in favor of the poor and weak. Job anticipates that YHWH will apply the same standard to the three friends: their show of wisdom will be exposed as self-serving when the divine Judge examines the proceedings. This is confirmed in the epilogue (42:7-9) where YHWH explicitly rebukes the three friends for not speaking rightly about God.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Will not his majesty terrify you, and the dread of him fall upon you?' The divine terror (<em>śeʾēṯ</em>, majesty; <em>paḥad</em>, dread/terror) was a recognized theological category — the presence of the divine was inherently terrifying to humans (Rudolf Otto's <em>numinosum</em> had ancient roots in this category). In the OT, YHWH's approach is regularly accompanied by fear and trembling (Exod 19:16-18; Isa 6:1-5). Eliphaz himself invoked this divine terror in his night vision (4:14-15). Job uses the same category to warn the friends: the very divine majesty they invoke as the source of their authority should terrify them when they consider what they have done by speaking falsely on God's behalf.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Your maxims are proverbs of ashes, your defenses are defenses of clay.' The wisdom tradition's understanding of material durability provides the metaphor: ashes (<em>ʾēper</em>) and clay (<em>ḥōmer</em>) are the most fragile and impermanent substances — they return to dust, have no structural integrity, and cannot bear weight. The friends' <em>ziḵrōnîm</em> (maxims, memorable sayings — the core of the wisdom tradition's oral transmission) are ash-maxims: impressive-sounding but structurally void. In the ANE context, wisdom proverbs were valued for having permanent truth-value, like inscriptions in stone; Job dismisses their counsel as inscription in ash — it disappears when touched.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Let me have silence, and I will speak, and let come on me what may.' Job's demand for silence before his formal speech invokes court procedure: witnesses and advocates were required to speak in turn, and the assembled hearing had to remain silent during formal testimony. The phrase 'let come on me what may' (<em>yaʿăḇōr ʿālay māh</em>) is a formal oath of willingness to bear consequences — a legal declaration that Job accepts the risk of his assertion. In ancient legal culture, this kind of formal declaration of willingness to be judged was a recognized form of oath-taking that intensified the seriousness of what followed.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Why should I take my flesh in my teeth and put my life in my hand?' The idiom 'take one's life in one's hand' is an ancient expression for extreme personal risk — used in Judg 12:3 and 1 Sam 19:5 for military courage in life-threatening situations. Job's rhetorical question establishes that speaking directly to God constitutes extreme risk. In the ancient world, direct petition to a king or deity was dangerous: the Persian court's rule that only those summoned might approach the king (Esth 4:11) reflects a broader ANE protocol about unsolicited access to divine or royal presence. Job acknowledges that what he is about to do is technically suicidal, but he is willing to bear the risk.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Though he slay me, I will hope in him; yet I will argue my ways to his face.' This verse is among the most debated in the book. The traditional reading ('though he slay me, yet will I trust in him' — KJV) reflects one textual tradition, while another reads 'I have no hope' (ESV margin). The honor-shame context illuminates both: in the ANE tradition, approaching the king with a petition even knowing you might be killed was understood as the highest form of courage and loyalty. Job's willingness to argue his case in the face of potential divine violence is not sinful defiance but the honor code that demands justice even at personal cost — the same code that makes the honor-shame world legible.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'This will be my salvation, that the godless shall not come before him.' The claim that approaching God directly constitutes salvation draws on the ancient theology of divine presence as the highest good. In Israelite tradition, exile from the divine presence was the ultimate punishment (Gen 4:14: Cain cast from YHWH's presence; Ps 51:11: 'do not cast me away from your presence'). Job's logic: the fact that he can approach God with his case — even this dangerous approach — is evidence that he is not among the <em>ḥānēp̄</em> (godless, profane). The godless could not appear before the divine judge; Job's very willingness to do so demonstrates his integrity.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Keep listening to my words, and let my declaration be in your ears.' The formal demand for attention (<em>šōmōaʿ wəhôḏiʿēnî</em>) uses the standard form of the prophetic call to attention (Isa 1:2, 10; Deut 6:4). By using this prophetic attention-formula, Job elevates his legal statement to the status of formal proclamation. The audience is not just the three friends but implicitly the divine court: Job is making his declaration before the divine assembly as well as the human witnesses — a public record of his legal position.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Behold, I have prepared my case; I know that I shall be in the right.' The legal vocabulary reaches its peak: <em>mišpāṭ</em> (case, judgment, legal ruling) prepared (<em>ʿāraḵ</em>, the verb for setting out a military formation or a legal argument in order — also used for arranging the showbread, Lev 24:8, and the battle line, 1 Sam 17:8). 'I know that I shall be in the right' is not presumptuous confidence but the honest claim of someone who has examined his own conscience and found no specific sin to account for his suffering. The forensic context demands this claim: without it, there is no case to bring before the divine judge.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Who is there who will contend with me? For then I would be silent and die.' The challenge to a counter-adversary reflects the ancient legal practice of adversarial proceedings. In Mesopotamian and Israelite law, the accuser and the accused faced each other directly; without an accuser, there was no case. Job's challenge: if no one can demonstrate a specific charge against him, the case collapses and he could die with equanimity. The rhetorical force: the friends have been making accusations without formal charges, and Job is demanding they either formalize their charge with specifics or admit they have none — a move that exposes their rhetoric as assertion without evidence.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Only grant me two things, then I will not hide myself from your face.' The formal petition to God uses the legal language of negotiating the conditions of a judicial hearing. In ancient Near Eastern legal procedure, the parties to a dispute could negotiate the terms of the hearing. The hiding from the divine face (<em>pānêḵā</em>) echoes the fear of Adam hiding from YHWH in Gen 3:8 and David's plea 'do not hide your face from me' (Ps 27:9). Job frames his terror not as guilt (like Adam) but as the natural response to divine power that must be adjusted before the hearing can proceed fairly — the divine majesty must be calibrated for the hearing to be just.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Withdraw your hand far from me, and let not dread of you terrify me.' Job's two conditions are: (1) removal of the divine hand of affliction — the physical suffering that makes clear thinking and speaking impossible, and (2) removal of divine terror — the overwhelming psychological weight that prevents coherent argument. The ancient petitioner approaching a king relied on the king's grace to set aside his majesty temporarily; Job is formally requesting the divine analogue of that royal courtesy. This is not atheism or rebellion — it is the highest form of taking divine justice seriously: insisting that the conditions for a fair hearing be met.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Then call, and I will answer; or let me speak, and you reply to me.' The alternating structure of the proposed hearing — God speaks/Job answers, or Job speaks/God replies — is the format of the ancient Near Eastern divine oracle or judicial proceeding. The prophetic consultation and the temple oracle both involved alternating speech: the petitioner spoke, the divine response came through the priest or prophet. Job is asking for a direct, unmediated form of this exchange. The divine response in the whirlwind speeches (chs. 38-41) provides exactly this alternating structure — but God asks the questions rather than answering Job's.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'How many are my iniquities and my sins? Make me know my transgression and my sin.' The request for a specific accounting uses all three major Hebrew terms for moral failure: <em>ʿăwōnôṯ</em> (iniquities, the twisted/perverted), <em>ḥaṭṭāʾôṯ</em> (sins, the missing-the-mark), <em>pešaʿ</em> (transgression/rebellion). Job is not claiming absolute sinlessness — he uses all three categories — but demanding to know which specific offense accounts for the specific severity of his suffering. In ancient legal systems, the accused had a right to know the specific charges (cf. Hittite vassal treaties which specified exact obligations and their violations). The friends' refusal to specify charges is what makes their counsel both practically and legally unhelpful.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Why do you hide your face and count me as your enemy?' The divine hiding of the face (<em>hastēr pānîm</em>) is one of the most theologically significant categories in the OT. In the covenant relationship, the divine face shining on the covenant partner was the supreme blessing (Num 6:25); hiding the face was the covenant curse (Deut 31:17-18; 32:20). Psalms 10, 13, 22, 44, 88, and 102 all express this experience. Job connects his suffering with this covenant category: divine absence communicates enmity when Job knows he is not YHWH's enemy — it is a false message sent by the structure of his circumstances that his conscience contests.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'Will you frighten a driven leaf and pursue dry stubble?' The images of the driven leaf and dry stubble are chosen for their extreme vulnerability: they are among the weakest and most easily destroyed natural objects. In ANE military vocabulary, the pursuit of a scattered army was described using images of pursuing fleeing things — but pursuing a single windblown leaf with full divine power is grotesquely disproportionate. The disproportion is the rhetorical point: if YHWH treats Job as an enemy requiring full divine pursuit, the scale of the response is entirely inappropriate to any sin Job might have committed.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'For you write bitter things against me and make me inherit the iniquities of my youth.' The 'writing bitter things' draws on the ancient practice of recording court verdicts in writing — indictments were literally inscribed in legal documents that became permanent records. In Mesopotamia, the divine record of human deeds was a central theological concept: the divine tablets of destiny recorded all things, and judgment books were consulted at the annual divine assembly (reflected in Dan 7 and the Jewish Day of Atonement theology). Job's complaint: YHWH has written bitter charges against him, and the scroll includes sins of youth (<em>ʿăwōnôṯ nəʿûrāy</em>) that Job thought had been settled through the regular atonement system.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'You put my feet in the stocks and watch all my paths; you set a limit for the soles of my feet.' Archaeological evidence of leg-irons and stocks has been found in Israelite contexts — they were used for both prisoners and slaves in the ancient Near East. But the verse adds divine surveillance ('you watch all my paths') which elevates the restraint to a theological statement about total divine monitoring. The limiting of the feet's reach suggests divine marking — Job is tagged and tracked, unable to escape divine attention even in his suffering. The same divine omnipresence celebrated in Ps 139 ('where shall I flee from your presence?') is here experienced as surveillance rather than comfort.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'One wastes away like a rotten thing, like a garment that is moth-eaten.' The conclusion of Job's judicial address uses images of decay — rotten wood (<em>rāqāḇ</em>) and moth-eaten cloth (<em>ʿāš</em>). Both images emphasize the fragility and temporariness of human existence. This sets up the mortality meditation in ch14: having made his legal case, Job now reflects on the broader context in which the legal dispute takes place — the brevity of the human life that is being treated as a major threat requiring divine prosecution. The legal intensity of ch13 gives way to the existential lament of ch14.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>'Man who is born of a woman is few of days and full of trouble.' The universal meditation on human mortality draws on the wisdom tradition's two central observations: brevity (<em>qaṣar yāmîm</em>) and trouble (<em>śāḇaʿ rōgez</em>). In ANE wisdom literature, the brevity of life was universal — the Gilgamesh Epic opens with Enkidu's death and Gilgamesh's subsequent quest for immortality; the Egyptian Dialogue of a Man with His Soul meditates on death as relief. The phrase 'born of a woman' emphasizes biological creatureliness — birth through a woman was the universal mark of mortality in the ancient world (cf. Job 25:4; Gal 4:4: 'born of woman' as the formula for full human participation in the mortal condition).</p>",
    "2": "<p>'He comes out like a flower and withers; he flees like a shadow and continues not.' The flower (<em>ṣîṣ</em>) and shadow (<em>ṣēl</em>) as metaphors for human brevity are widespread in ANE and OT poetry. The flower metaphor appears in Ps 103:15-16 and Isa 40:6-8 ('All flesh is like grass... the grass withers, the flower fades'). The shadow metaphor appears throughout the Psalms and in Eccl 6:12; 8:13. These metaphors were culturally resonant because they acknowledged what ordinary experience confirmed: human life is beautiful but momentary. The imagery here is not pessimism but the wisdom tradition's realistic anthropology.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'And do you open your eyes on such a one and bring me into judgment with you?' The switch from the universal 'man' to the personal 'me' is rhetorically powerful: having established the universal fragility of human existence, Job makes it personal — the divine Judge is bringing legal proceedings against this fragile, short-lived creature. In the ANE context, the disproportion was culturally obvious: bringing a great king's full judicial process to bear on a flower or a shadow would be absurd. Job uses the universalizing wisdom tradition to make a specific complaint about the theological inappropriateness of divine prosecution of mortal human beings.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Who can bring a clean thing out of an unclean? There is not one.' This aphoristic question draws on ancient purity theology. In Levitical law, ritual purity was not transmissible from the impure to the pure — unclean things contaminate clean things, but purity cannot be derived from impurity. The question is not primarily about moral sinlessness but about ontological creaturely status: the human being born of woman cannot transcend the limitations of the fallen creaturely condition. In Second Temple period interpretation, this verse became central in discussions of original sin and the inherited tendency toward failure — the theological tradition of Rom 5:12-14 has deep roots in exactly this wisdom observation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Since his days are determined, and the number of his months is with you, and you have appointed his limits that he cannot pass.' The divine determination of human lifespan was a universal ANE theological assumption. In Mesopotamian theology, the 'days' and 'years' of kings were literally decreed in the divine tablets of destiny at the beginning of each year's divine assembly. In Israelite theology, Ps 139:16 reflects the same: 'in your book were written, every one of them, the days that were formed for me.' The <em>ḥuqqôṯāyw</em> (appointed limits, from <em>ḥāqaq</em>, to engrave/decree) suggests the permanence of legal inscription — the limits are not adjustable by human action or petition.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Look away from him and leave him alone, that he may enjoy, like a hired hand, his day.' The request 'look away from him' continues the protest of 7:16-19 where Job begged God to stop watching him for a moment. The hired hand (<em>śāḵîr</em>) was entitled to rest at the end of his work — Deut 24:15 required wages be paid before sundown, acknowledging the human dignity of the laborer's right to enjoyment of his earned rest. Job uses this labor-law category to argue that the human being deserves a temporary respite from divine scrutiny — even the most closely supervised laborer gets the end of the day.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'For there is hope for a tree, if it is cut down, that it will sprout again, and that its shoots will not cease.' The tree-stump image is a powerful contrast with human mortality. Certain trees were known to regenerate from stumps — the felling of a tree was not necessarily its death. Isaiah would use this imagery for the Davidic stump (Isa 6:13; 11:1: 'a shoot from the stump of Jesse'). In Mesopotamian mythology, the tree of life (<em>kiškanu</em> tree) was the symbol of divine vitality; its inaccessibility to humans after the fall (Gen 3:22-24) encoded the human condition of mortality. The tree's capacity for regrowth is contrasted with human death's apparent finality.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Though its root grow old in the earth, and its stump die in the soil, yet at the scent of water it will bud and put out branches like a young plant.' The scent (<em>rêaḥ</em>) of water triggering the stump's revival is a botanical observation ancient audiences would have recognized — trees in the dry climate of the Levant could appear dead through the dry season and revive dramatically with the winter rains. The fundamental importance of water in the ANE agricultural world was not just practically necessary but theologically laden, associated with divine blessing and life (Ps 1:3; Jer 17:8). The contrast with the human corpse, which does not similarly revive at the scent of water, heightens the tragedy of human mortality.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Yet at the scent of water it will bud and put out branches like a young plant.' The simile's force depends on the contrast with vv.10-12 where the human equivalent of revival is explicitly denied. The wisdom context: the tree metaphor for human flourishing was conventional in the Psalms and Proverbs (Ps 1:3; 52:8; 92:12-14; Prov 11:28), but Job reverses the convention — it is the tree that revives, not the human. The conventional metaphor for covenant blessing has been turned against itself to highlight the anomaly of human mortality: the non-living tree is more alive than the dead human.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'But a man dies and is laid low; man breathes his last, and where is he?' The <em>gāḇer</em> (the strong man — emphasizing not weakness but the prime of human strength) dies. <em>Wayyigwaʿ</em> (breathes his last — from <em>gāwaʿ</em>, the basic verb for dying) uses the same root as the divine life-breath of Gen 2:7 in reverse: what God breathed in, death breathes out. The rhetorical question 'where is he?' (<em>ʾayyeh</em>) is the great question of mortality in ancient literature — Gilgamesh asked this of the dead Enkidu; the Psalms ask it of the absent divine presence. Job's use reflects both the wisdom tradition's honest acknowledgment of death's finality and his specific longing for post-mortem vindication.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'As waters fail from a lake and a river wastes away and dries up.' The dying lake and evaporating river are images of irreversible loss. In the Middle East, the drying up of a wadi or lake was a recognized catastrophe — the periodic drying of desert lakes and the seasonal disappearance of rivers were observed phenomena that symbolized total, complete loss. ANE wisdom poetry used water-loss imagery for death (the drying Nile in Egyptian wisdom poetry symbolizes life's end). Job's use is particularly poignant given the wadi-friends imagery of ch6: the unreliable wadis now become an image of the unreliable continuation of human life itself.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'So a man lies down and rises not again; till the heavens are no more he will not awake or be roused out of his sleep.' The phrase 'till the heavens are no more' (<em>ʿaḏ-bəlî šāmayim</em>) is a temporal absolute — the heavens were the most permanent feature of the created order in ancient thought. In Babylonian cosmology, the heavens were the first creation and would be the last to pass away. Job's statement reflects the pre-resurrection anthropology of early Israelite belief: the dead do not rise until a cosmic transformation of the most fundamental kind. The second-century BCE development of explicit resurrection belief (Dan 12:2: 'Many of those who sleep in the dust of the earth shall awake') represents the full flowering of what Job here laments as an apparent impossibility.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Oh that you would hide me in Sheol, that you would conceal me until your wrath is past, that you would appoint me a set time, and remember me!' The longing for Sheol as a hiding place is a remarkable theological reversal: Sheol was normally feared as the place of divine absence (Ps 88:3-5; 115:17-18), but Job desires it as temporary refuge from divine wrath. The <em>mōʿēd</em> (appointed time — the same term for the sacred assembly calendar, used in the festival system) suggests that Job envisions a temporary term in Sheol followed by divine remembrance and recall. This is the OT's earliest sustained movement toward resurrection hope: not yet the explicit resurrection of Daniel 12 but the longing that would eventually require resurrection as its answer.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'If a man dies, shall he live again? All the days of my service I would wait, till my renewal should come.' The question 'shall he live again?' is the book's most direct engagement with personal resurrection. The ancient Near Eastern background: Canaanite religion had myths of dying-and-rising deities (Baal's annual death and resurrection in the Baal-Mot myth), but the Israelite tradition was more cautious about applying this mythology to human beings. Job's question is genuinely open — the Hebrew is interrogative, not declarative — but his willingness to wait through his 'service' (<em>ṣāḇāʾ</em>, the military conscription term from 7:1) for his 'renewal' (<em>ḥălîp̄āṯî</em>, relief from military duty) suggests a hope that does not yet fully trust itself.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'You would call, and I would answer you; you would long for the work of your hands.' The vision of divine calling and human response draws on covenant relationship vocabulary: in the covenant, YHWH calls and the covenant partner responds. The phrase 'the work of your hands' (<em>maʿăśēh yāḏêḵā</em>) is the language of creation-love: humans as the personal craft of the divine artisan (Ps 138:8; 143:5). Job's hope: the God who made him will not ultimately abandon his own workmanship — that the divine creative investment in the human being carries with it an obligation not to simply discard it at death. This is one of the earliest theological arguments for resurrection: if God made us, God has a stake in our continued existence.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'For then you would number my steps; you would not keep watch over my sin.' In the hoped-for future state, divine numbering of steps (<em>tispōr ṣeʿādāy</em>) would be a benevolent act of care rather than the hostile surveillance of the present. The divine watching oscillates between hostile and caring in chs. 13-14: the same divine attention Job now experiences as persecution would, in the restored relationship, be experienced as tender concern. In Second Temple Judaism, the angelological tradition developed the idea of guardian angels who recorded deeds — a development of exactly this image toward a benign form of divine attention.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'My transgression would be sealed up in a bag, and you would cover over my iniquity.' The sealed bag (<em>ṣərûr</em>) for transgression and the covered iniquity use the imagery of archival storage and permanent closure. In ANE legal practice, settled cases were physically sealed: clay tablets were enclosed in clay envelopes, and the act of sealing indicated finality. Job's hope is for divine archival closure of his record — the charges permanently sealed and stored rather than kept active as standing indictments. The connection to atonement theology: the Hebrew <em>ṭûaḥ</em> (to cover over) resonates with the annual atonement ritual in which sin was symbolically removed and sealed away.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'But the mountain falls and crumbles away, and the rock is removed from its place.' The geological images of mountain erosion and rock removal return to the dominant motif of ch14: the permanence of nature vs. the impermanence of human life. In the ancient world, mountains were the dwelling places of the gods (Mount Olympus, Mount Zaphon, Mount Sinai/Horeb) and symbols of permanence (Ps 125:1-2; Isa 54:10: 'the mountains may depart and the hills be removed'). But the erosion of even mountains is gradual and process-oriented, which shifts the register from the sudden death of ch14:10 to the slow wearing-down of the next image.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'The waters wear away the stones; the torrents wash away the soil of the earth; so you destroy the hope of man.' The water-wearing-stone image captures a process that ancient people could observe over time: the smooth stones of riverbeds, the carved rock formations of wadis, all testified to the patient erosion of water over stone. The word <em>tiqwāh</em> (hope) has appeared earlier in Job and throughout the dialogues — the friends claimed the righteous have it (5:16; 8:13; 11:18, 20) while Job consistently experiences its absence. Here the destruction of hope is attributed directly to divine action, continuing the judicial-complaint register of ch13: the same divine power that pursues Job through the law (ch13) wears away his hope through time (ch14).</p>",
    "20": "<p>'You prevail forever against him, and he passes; you change his face, and send him away.' The divine triumph over the human being is total: <em>tittəqēp̄ehû</em> (you overpower him) uses the language of martial or legal victory — YHWH wins the contest definitively. The changing of the face (<em>mǝšanneh pānāyw</em>) refers to the visible marks of death on the human face — the ancient world observed that the face changes at death, reflecting the departure of the animating spirit. The sending away (<em>tǝšallḥēhû</em>) uses royal-dismissal language: when the audience is over, the petitioner is sent from the king's presence. Death is the final, irrevocable dismissal from the divine presence — unless God calls back, as Job has just dared to hope in v.15.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'His sons come to honor, and he does not know it; they are brought low, and he perceives it not.' The ignorance of the dead about events in the living world was a consistent feature of ancient Near Eastern afterlife anthropology. In Mesopotamian thought, the dead in the underworld (the land of no-return) were cut off from the affairs of the living; the <em>etemmu</em> (ghost/shade) required regular funerary offerings precisely because it had no other access to the world of the living. In the OT, Sheol is consistently described as a place of silence and isolation (Ps 31:17; 88:5, 12; 115:17; Eccl 9:5: 'the dead know nothing'). Job's observation that the dead father is unaware of his children's fate is a particularly poignant form of the death-as-total-loss argument.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'He feels only the pain of his own body, and he mourns only for himself.' The closing verse focuses the dying man's experience entirely inward: the relational world (children, community, honor/shame status) recedes, and all that remains is the somatic experience of dying and the solitary mourning of the self. The ancient mourning practices — tearing of garments, sitting in ashes, lament poetry, communal gathering — were all external and social; the dying body can no longer participate in these communal forms of grief. The verse captures the profound loneliness of dying: the social creature who lived in community and honor ends in isolated bodily suffering and individual lament. This is also the implicit description of Job's own situation — the ash heap is the place where communal life has collapsed into solitary mourning.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    d = load_comm('mkt-context', 'job')
    before = sum(len(v) for v in d.values())
    merge_comm(d, JOB_CONTEXT_12_14)
    after = sum(len(v) for v in d.values())
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'job', d)
    for ch in ['12', '13', '14']:
        vs = sorted(d.get(ch, {}).keys(), key=int)
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vs)} verses')
    print(f'wrote {after - before} new verses ({after} total)')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
